What are we talking about ?

Introduction

In 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a fleet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime.

Until now, Cyclistics marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships.

Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members.

Cyclistics finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, and believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers,

The director of marketing has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members

ASK Process

  1. Marketing team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.
  2. The marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ ?
  3. Why casual riders would buy a membership ?
  4. How digital media could affect their marketing tactics ?

Objective

Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members

trips_2014_Q30809 <- read.csv('Divvy_Trips_2014-Q3-0809.csv')
trips_2014_Q4 <- read.csv('Divvy_Trips_2014-Q4.csv')
#clean columns name : make sure that columns names are unique and change data type of columns to suitable format

                   mutate(from_station_id = as.character(from_station_id), 
                          to_station_id = as.character(to_station_id),
                          starttime = mdy_hm(starttime),
                          stoptime = mdy_hm(stoptime))

trips_2014_Q307 <- clean_names(trips_2014_Q307) %>% 
                   mutate(from_station_id = as.character(from_station_id), 
                          to_station_id = as.character(to_station_id),
                          starttime = mdy_hm(starttime),
                          stoptime = mdy_hm(stoptime))

trips_2014_Q30809 <- clean_names(trips_2014_Q30809) %>% 
                     mutate(from_station_id = as.character(from_station_id), 
                           to_station_id = as.character(to_station_id),
                           starttime = mdy_hm(starttime),
                           stoptime = mdy_hm(stoptime))

trips_2014_Q4 <- clean_names(trips_2014_Q4) %>% 
                 mutate(from_station_id = as.character(from_station_id), 
                        to_station_id = as.character(to_station_id),
                        starttime = mdy_hm(starttime),
                        stoptime = mdy_hm(stoptime))
#join all data into data frame
trips_2014 <- bind_rows(trips_2014_Q1Q2, trips_2014_Q307, trips_2014_Q30809, trips_2014_Q4)
#glimpse(trips_2014)
#Transform data add columns 'ride_length_mins', 'day_of_week'
Sys.setlocale("LC_TIME", "English")
## [1] "English_United States.1252"
trips_2014_v2 <- trips_2014 %>% 
                 select(-tripduration) %>% 
                 mutate(ride_length_mins = difftime(stoptime, starttime, units = "mins")) %>% 
                 mutate(day_of_week = wday(starttime, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE))

Analyze & Visualization

Analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends [2014 - 2019]

#Analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends


#transform data to summarize number of trips, number of stations and avg_ride_length per quarter 
trips_2014_v3 <- trips_2014_v2 %>%
                 mutate(yearqtr = as.yearqtr(starttime)) %>% 
                 group_by(yearqtr,usertype) %>% 
                 drop_na() %>%
                 summarize(number_of_trips_per_qtr = n(), 
                           number_of_stations = n_distinct(from_station_id),
                           avg_ride_length_mins = round(mean(ride_length_mins)))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'yearqtr' (override with `.groups` argument)
trips_2015_v3 <- trips_2015_v2 %>%
                 mutate(yearqtr = as.yearqtr(starttime)) %>% 
                 group_by(yearqtr,usertype) %>% 
                 drop_na() %>%
                 summarize(number_of_trips_per_qtr = n(), 
                           number_of_stations = n_distinct(from_station_id),
                           avg_ride_length_mins = round(mean(ride_length_mins)))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'yearqtr' (override with `.groups` argument)
trips_2016_v3 <- trips_2016_v2 %>%
                 mutate(yearqtr = as.yearqtr(starttime)) %>% 
                 group_by(yearqtr,usertype) %>% 
                 drop_na() %>%
                 summarize(number_of_trips_per_qtr = n(), 
                           number_of_stations = n_distinct(from_station_id),
                           avg_ride_length_mins = round(mean(ride_length_mins)))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'yearqtr' (override with `.groups` argument)
trips_2017_v3 <- trips_2017_v2 %>%
                 mutate(yearqtr = as.yearqtr(starttime)) %>% 
                 group_by(yearqtr,usertype) %>% 
                 drop_na() %>%
                 summarize(number_of_trips_per_qtr = n(), 
                           number_of_stations = n_distinct(from_station_id),

                 unite(start_end_id, c("start_station_id", "end_station_id"), sep = "_", na.rm = TRUE) %>%

Conclusion

From Historical bike data since 2014-2019 represent

  • numbers of trips increase every year, especially annual Third Quarter (Q3)
  • mostly user is Subscriber(member)
  • average ride length (minutes) Casual(usertype = Customer and Dependent) higher than Subscriber(member)

From 2020 bike data represent

  • on Q3 2020 have highest number of trips
  • on Q3 2020 number of trips of Member greater than Casual
  • on Sunday and Saturday, number of trips of Casual user greater than Member user
  • Numbers of trips on Sunday and Saturday, Casual greater than Member since 11am to Midnight
  • Average ride length of Casual higher than Member
  • Average ride length of Casual ~48.3 minutes | Average ride length of Member ~15.78 minutes
